<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="product-launch">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-planning</domain>
    <summary>Coordinated product introduction to market: positioning, assets, channel, and team readiness. Planning starts 6–8 weeks out to generate awareness and initial adoption momentum.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>product-launch</tag>
      <tag>go-to-market</tag>
      <tag>marketing</tag>
      <tag>launch-planning</tag>
      <tag>product-hunt</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Product Launch</title>
    <summary>A product launch is a coordinated introduction of a product to its target market — not just a deployment, but a strategic moment to generate awareness and initial adoption. Planning starts 6–8 weeks out. Four components must be ready: positioning and messaging, assets (landing page, demo, docs), channels (email, social, communities), and coordination (internal team readiness, external partners).</summary>
    <why>
      <p>"Just put it out there" launches produce a brief spike that disappears because no pre-launch audience was built, no messaging was aligned, and no one was ready to respond. A structured launch plan converts the deployment event into sustained user acquisition momentum.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Shipping a new product or major version that targets a new or expanded audience.</item>
        <item>Any launch where first-week metrics (signups, activations, media mentions) matter.</item>
        <item>Coordinating multiple channels and teams (marketing, engineering, support) toward a common date.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Internal releases or feature flags visible only to existing users — a changelog entry suffices.</item>
        <item>Bug fixes or performance improvements with no new user-facing surface.</item>
        <item>Continuous rollouts to a known user base — use a release notes workflow instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="launch-types">
      <rule>
        <statement>Choose launch type based on risk and audience size: soft launch (limited audience, low risk) → beta launch (early adopters, medium risk) → full launch (public, high risk). Do not skip stages for high-risk products.</statement>
        <rationale>Full public launches are hard to walk back. A soft or beta launch lets you fix critical issues before they affect reputation at scale.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="8-week-countdown">
      <rule>
        <statement>Start planning 6–8 weeks before launch day. T-8: define strategy. T-6: create assets. T-4: build pre-launch audience. T-2: finalize coordination. T-1: final checks. T-Day: execute. T+1: monitor and respond. T+2: retrospective.</statement>
        <rationale>Launches planned in the final week lack pre-launch audience, have untested assets, and produce no momentum. The 8-week timeline is the minimum for a coordinated launch with measurable impact.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="four-required-components">
      <rule>
        <statement>Positioning and messaging must be locked before asset creation. Key message, value proposition, target audience, and differentiation all need to be agreed before writing copy.</statement>
        <rationale>Assets built before messaging alignment diverge and require rework. Messaging is the foundation; assets are the expression.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Minimum viable launch assets: landing page, demo or screenshots, announcement email, social posts, basic documentation. All must be ready at T-2.</statement>
        <rationale>Missing assets on launch day create a gap between awareness (the announcement) and conversion (the landing page). Even one missing asset breaks the funnel.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Build a pre-launch audience before launch day: waitlist, email subscribers, social following, community relationships. The audience determines the floor for Day 1 metrics.</statement>
        <rationale>A launch to zero audience produces zero traction regardless of product quality. Pre-launch audience building is the highest-leverage activity in the 8-week window.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Coordinate internally before going public: support team briefed, on-call engineer named, monitoring dashboards ready, social media accounts active and monitored.</statement>
        <rationale>Launch day without internal coordination produces delayed responses to issues and confusion about who owns what. Each role needs to know its responsibilities before T-Day.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="launch-day-timing">
      <rule>
        <statement>Launch on Tuesday or Wednesday, not Friday. For Product Hunt, launch at 12:01 AM Pacific Time to maximize voting window.</statement>
        <rationale>Friday launches run into the weekend news cycle. Product Hunt voting resets at midnight PT; launching at 12:01 AM gives the maximum 24-hour window for votes.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="example-product-hunt-launch">
      <example type="good">
        <note>AI writing tool. Goal: top-5 Product of the Day. 4-week pre-launch preparation. Outcome: #3 PD, 1,200 signups.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Product: AI Writing Tool
Goal: #1 Product of the Day (stretch) / Top 5 (target)

T-4 weeks: Build relationships with top hunters; identify 3 candidates
T-2 weeks: Assets complete (listing copy, gallery, first comment draft)
           Gather 5 customer testimonials
T-1 week:  Brief 200+ supporters; schedule all announcement posts
T-Day:     12:01 AM PT — listing live
           9 AM: Email announcement to list (2,400 subscribers)
           10 AM: Twitter/LinkedIn thread
           All day: Respond to every Product Hunt comment within 30 min

Result: #3 Product of the Day, 1,200 signups day 1, 340 active at day 7
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="example-beta-launch">
      <example type="good">
        <note>Analytics dashboard. Goal: 100 qualified beta users. Staged rollout from existing customers to waitlist.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Product: Analytics Dashboard
Goal: 100 beta users with 40%+ week-1 active rate

Stage 1: Soft launch to 50 existing power customers (week 1-2)
         Gather structured feedback; fix critical UX issues
Stage 2: Open to waitlist (500 people) — accept first 100 who complete onboarding
         Send personal invite emails (not mass blast)
Stage 3: Waitlist users who are declined go to "notify me for GA" list

Result: 100 beta users, 42% active in week 1,
        12 critical bugs found and fixed before GA,
        waitlist-to-GA conversion: 68%
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Planning starts the week before launch day.</description>
      <reason>One week is not enough to build a pre-launch audience, create and review assets, coordinate partners, or set up monitoring. Minimum: 6 weeks for a meaningful launch, 8 weeks for a high-impact one.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Launching on a Friday.</description>
      <reason>Friday launches lose the Monday-Tuesday news cycle. Most journalists and influencers are not covering tech news Friday afternoon. Tuesday-Wednesday gives the full week's coverage window.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Same message posted verbatim to every channel.</description>
      <reason>Twitter audiences, email subscribers, and LinkedIn followers have different contexts and norms. Copy-pasting produces content that feels wrong in each channel and reduces engagement in all of them.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>No pre-launch audience — the product is announced to a cold start.</description>
      <reason>Without an email list, waitlist, or community following, Day 1 signups depend entirely on algorithm and press pickup — both unreliable. Building even 500 subscribers before launch transforms the baseline metric.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>No monitoring on launch day — the team is focused on announcements, not product health.</description>
      <reason>Launch day is peak load and peak visibility for bugs. Server errors and broken flows during the announcement window permanently affect conversion. Assign a dedicated on-call engineer before posting anything.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>No post-launch retrospective.</description>
      <reason>Launch learnings are the highest-value data point for the next launch. What channel outperformed, which asset under-converted, what the team would change — all disappear if not captured within 2 weeks.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/launch-plan.md" purpose="Full launch plan: overview, audience, timeline, asset checklist, channel strategy, metrics"/>
      <template path="templates/launch-day-checklist.md" purpose="Hour-by-hour launch day checklist: pre-launch, go-live, announcement, monitoring, EOD"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
